4.0.0 Deployment

4.1.0 Local Deployment

After constructing the body of code within Google Colab and verifying it works as intended, the next logical step in the development of the project is to export the notebooks into functional local models on a local device, removing the need for constant access to a server and providing a higher level of integration between independent scripts whilst allowing the user to utilise their own local hardware with no limitations imposed by a third-party such as google.

4.1.1 Requirements

In order for the code to run correctly it must be executed on a python 3.8 compiler. The system also requires the following imports and at the time of writing is functional on the following versions:

  • Librosa 0.8.0
  • Torch 1.8.0
  • Torchvision 0.9.0
  • Torchaudio 0.8.0
  • Fastai 2.2.7
  • Fastaudio 0.1.4
  • Cuda 10.1

Librosa is an audio manipulation library used alongside fastaudio to convert audio files into raw meta data and melSpectrograms for analysis. Link: https://librosa.org/doc/latest/index.html

Torch is the fundamental library for machine learning and is the backbone of the fastai library which supports the entirety of this project. Torchaudio and torchvision are extensions of this library which provide more accurate analysis for audio and image-based datasets in training models. Link: https://pytorch.org/

Fastai and by extension fastaudio, as mentioned before, provide the structure for all models trained and developed within this project, therefore without all requirements being satisfied the project cannot operate.

4.1.2 Virtual Environments

Due to the different dependencies of the system and the need to maintain the systems usability in the future, it would not be suitable to simply download the required dependencies directly to the local machine as any future updates or changes pose a risk of creating a critical error within the project, especially considering the volatile nature of machine learning development and lack of version control.

For this reason, a python virtual environment is the most suitable method to maintain the systems usability without limiting the available libraries on the device. A virtual environment is a self-contained executable that can hold it’s own libraries and dependencies, separate to the main python executable of the device. This allows developers to maintain version control without limiting future development of other projects.

I order to create a virtual environment, open the command line by typing ‘cmd’ in the search bar and selecting the command line application. When opening the command line, right click and ensure to select ‘Run as Administrator’ to ensure there are no restrictions on the creation of the venv.

Using the change directory function, ‘cd c:\path\to\venv\location’, traverse the directory list to where you wish to store the venv, then type the following command: ‘python -m venv <venv name>’

After creating the virtual environment, it is necessary to activate it in order to begin installing required libraries. To activate the venv, use the following command line prompt: ‘sample_venv\Scripts\activate.bat’

It is apparent that the venv is active as the name will appear in brackets beside the current working directory:

Once installed and activated, the required libraries can then be installed using the pip installer within python as follows:

‘python -m pip install <library Name> == <version number>’

Once finished with the venv, it can be deactivated by simply typing ‘deactivate’ into the command line. It is apparent that this is successful as the venv name no longer appears in brackets beside the current working directory.

Now the virtual environment is fully functional it is possible to begin adjusting the notebooks for local execution.

As google colab had a local environment for storing datasets and other related files in a standardised area, it was essential to define the necessary file paths between all the resources that the project required. This was done within a JSON file due to the relatively low storage requirements and powerful storage structure. For those not familiar with JSON files, the following guide is incredibly useful: https://realpython.com/python-json/ .

4.1.4 Running the code

Now the code is optimised, it must be executed within the virtual environment to make use of all the imported dependencies. In order to do this, the venv must be executed as shown above and then the code can be executed directly from the command line using the code: ‘python <script name>.py’

This initialises the python.exe stored within the venv to run the files, ensuring that all necessary dependencies are available.

4.1.5 Compiling the code

Once the code was running as intended, the next step was to package into an executable file that can be ran by the user without the need to access the source code. In order to this, the pyinstaller package is an effective tool which is easily accessible within the command line by simply using the following code: ‘python -m pip install pyinstaller’

Once pyinstaller is availible, the .py files can be converted into a .pyc file by using the following code:

‘pyinstaller --onefile <filename>.py’

Once the files are compiled, they can be executed similarly to .py files using the ‘python <filename>.pyc’.

To link all the compiled python files, windows batch files were used to activate the venv and execute the files without the need for direct command line access, improving the overall usability of the system. Batch files act as executable files that require a double click to run the command line commands within them such as this:

Then, by using a basic GUI interface and the subprocess library within python, the batch files were able to be linked to a single file that was user friendly and accessible to users of any background.

4.1.6 Drawbacks

The initial prototype, whilst functional in its execution, was far from perfect and had several non-critical errors and inefficiencies.

Due to the location of the paths JSON, the RUN_ME file could only be initialised by using the batch file contained within experiments which added a level of complexity for the end user.

The use of absolute file paths in any capacity limits the flexibility of the system and creates a rigid structure that has the potential to crash if any changes are made to the directory during the execution of the code.

As the tabular and CNN learner are linked to the same directory, on execution they overwrite the exported model of the other which limits the ability of the prediction model, especially as it is only optimised for the CNN.

Furthermore, due to the .pyc files being stored in the parent directory, the deployment folder containing the trained model does not act as a self-contained package which can be downloaded and ran to create predictions.

A critical error within the overall deployment of the virtual environment is that it can only be used on the machine it was created due to the use of absolute file paths within the environment itself. As this is auto generated it will require a unique solution to overcome the problem and make the process of training machine learning models seamless for end users.

4.2.0 Application Development

4.2.1 Directory Structure

To improve the overall structure of the system I implemented the following directory structure:

(1) Auto-ml-env is the virtual environment containing the python.exe with all the necessary dependencies to run the project.

(2) Datasets consists of 2 sub-directories:

(i) Train contains the data required to train a model

(ii) Test contains the data required for running predictions and assessing the model’s accuracy.

(3) Experiments contains the JSON file containing all the necessary file paths to link the system together. The folder also contains the batch files to execute each module within the virtual environments python executable.

(4) Trained_cnn contains the exported model as well as the results JSON of the training model. The directory also contains the necessary source code to run predictions and can be downloaded as an independent file to run predictions, given that all the dependencies on the system are valid.

(5) Trained_tabular contains the exported model as well as the results JSON of the training model. However, at present the prediction script for the tabular model is not ready and is still being developed.

(6) Training_cnn simply contains the source code for training a CNN.

(7) Training_tabular simply contains the source code for training a tabular model.

4.2.2 Refinements

From the initial prototype, the major error to be addressed was the creation and initialisation the virtual environment on the end-user’s local machine. Using the python import ‘subprocess’, I was able to generate a basic statement to initialise the venv with all necessary dependencies. As this process is resource intensive and requires the installation of dependencies from the web, it was essential to minimise its execution as to improve the performance of the system therefore it is only implemented if the ‘auto-ml-env’ directory is unavailable.

Furthermore, by using the OS.chdir function, the RUN_ME.pyc file was able to run independently and access all required batch files whilst maintaining the directory structure as follows:

Where path is the relative file path to the experiments folder.

The absolute file path references were removed from the JSON and replaced with relative paths to provide a greater degree of flexibility. For those not familiar with relative file paths the following guide is a useful introduction: https://realpython.com/absolute-vs-relative-python-imports/

By removing the absolute file paths, it further simplified the initial start up of the program as the paths can be used on any directory and do not need to be constantly verified.

4.2.3 Code Run Through

To begin running the programme, double click the RUN_ME.cpython-38.pyc file contained within the parent directory:

As the ‘auto-ml-env’ folder is not present this will invoke the pip install function to build the dependencies, resulting in the creation of the venv:

Once the venv is created, the GUI will appear on screen with a range of options:

(1) Train Audio CNN triggers the process of training a Convolutional Neural Network, using the .wav files stored within the sub-directory ‘train’ of the ‘datasets’ directory, generating a pkl file and a results JSON of the training process (10 epochs).

(2) Train Tabular Learner triggers the process of training a tabular model, using the .wav files stored within the sub-directory ‘train’ of the ‘datasets’ directory, generating a pkl file and a results JSON of the training process (1000 epochs).

(3) Run CNN predictions allow the user to input a source file path and an output file path which then results in all .wav files within the source path being predicted and identified, with the results being outputted as a JSON within the output file path.

(4) Run Tabular Predictions is not yet implemented, but it is intended to allow the user to input a source file path and an output file path which then results in all .wav files within the source path being predicted and identified, with the results being outputted as a JSON within the output file path.

(5) Show CNN Results reads and returns the contents of the results JSON, generated after executing the Train Audio CNN function.

(6) Show Tabular Results reads and returns the contents of the results JSON, generated after executing the Train Tabular Learner function.
